equation_narrative.headline: Glycine's structural flexibility dominates mid-layers before polar asparagine prediction emerges late
equation_narrative.story: Position 60 in ubiquitin sits in a turn region between secondary structures, where the model initially assembles a representation emphasizing structural flexibility. Through layers 1-23, the logit lens reflects this with glycine peaking at 87% (L22), not because the model predicts glycine, but because the representation encodes turn-prone, conformationally flexible character. Only two structural contacts and three co-evolving positions provide limited constraint. The decision phase begins at L23-24 when asparagine-specific prediction channels activate. MLP neurons at L29-30 deliver the decisive votes, with N29:1362 contributing 1.256 projection and N30:2263 adding 0.783, driving asparagine from 29% to 83% in the final layers.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a representation dominated by structural context rather than sequence identity. Only 2 structural contacts and 3 co-evolving positions provide input, leaving the model to rely heavily on local sequence features. Early attention heads (L21:11 with 2.001 projection) read structural neighbors, while features at L9 and L18 encode turn-region character. The logit lens trajectory is striking: glycine rises from 7% (L0) to 87% (L22), reflecting the representation's encoding of conformational flexibility and turn-prone character typical of positions between secondary structures. This is not a glycine prediction—it's the model building a representation of what kind of position this is structurally. Small polar residues (S, T) also show moderate lens probability (17-23%) through mid-layers, consistent with the turn environment.
perception_phase.context_character: Turn region between secondary structures with minimal structural constraint (only 2 contacts) and moderate co-evolutionary coupling (3 positions). The representation through L23 encodes conformational flexibility and turn-prone character, with the logit lens projecting toward small, flexible residues (G, S, T) that reflect this structural environment rather than the specific chemistry required.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: only 2 residues within contact distance, providing minimal constraint compared to buried core positions
Co-evolutionary signal: 3 coupled positions provide moderate functional constraint

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L23-24 when asparagine-specific prediction channels activate. Glycine, which dominated the logit lens at 87% (L22) due to structural flexibility encoding, collapses as polar prediction features emerge. MLP layers 29-30 deliver the decisive push: N29:1362 contributes 1.256 projection (voting strongly for N with 1.256, V with 1.16, W with 1.019), N30:2263 adds 0.783, and N30:2733 contributes 0.725. Asparagine rises from 29% (L29) to 83% (L33), while glycine falls from 32% to 3%. The final attention heads at L31-32 refine the prediction, with L31:17 adding 2.329 projection.
decision_phase.transition: At L23, glycine still leads at 54% in the logit lens, but MLP neurons begin shifting toward asparagine with 1.76 total projection. L24 marks the true transition: asparagine-specific SAE features appear (F24:3213 with 9.71 proj, F24:3435 with 8.79 proj), and the representation shifts from encoding 'turn-flexible position' to predicting 'polar amide residue.' The logit lens lead changes from glycine to asparagine at L32 (33.8% → 53.0%).

candidates.narrative: Asparagine emerges decisively in the decision phase after being nearly absent in perception layers (6% at L23). The breakthrough occurs at L29-30 when highly specific MLP neurons activate: N29:1362 (1.256 proj), N30:2263 (0.783 proj), and N30:2733 (0.725 proj) all vote strongly for asparagine. SAE features at L30 show polar prediction channels: F30:698 (26.37 proj), F30:7792 (24.96 proj), and F30:1691 (23.67 proj). Asparagine rises from 29% (L29) to 83% (L33), overtaking glycine at L32 to claim victory.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L29, overtakes glycine L32, peaks L33 at 83%

candidates.narrative: Glycine dominates the logit lens from L8 through L23, peaking at 87% (L22), but this reflects the representation's encoding of structural flexibility rather than a glycine prediction. The model is building a representation of a turn-prone, conformationally unconstrained position—glycine's chemical character (no side chain, maximum flexibility) correlates strongly with this representation. As soon as asparagine-specific prediction features activate at L24+, glycine collapses from 54% (L23) to 32% (L29) to 3% (L33). The early lens dominance was never a belief—it was a structural characterization.

candidates.narrative: Serine maintains steady presence through perception layers (13-23% L8-L23) as the representation encodes small polar character consistent with turn regions. In the decision phase, serine receives moderate support from polar-voting neurons but lacks the specific prediction channels that drive asparagine. It finishes at 9% (L33), having peaked early at 23% (L0) when the model first reads the local sequence context with adjacent polar residues (T, D, Y).

candidates.narrative: Lysine briefly peaks at 16% (L18) when the representation explores charged character, possibly responding to nearby charged residues in the sequence context (K63, E64). However, lysine-specific prediction features never activate strongly in the decision phase, and it fades to 2% by L33. The mid-layer peak reflects the model testing whether this position requires positive charge for electrostatic interactions.

turning_points.description: Glycine reaches its logit-lens peak (87% at L22) as the representation fully encodes turn-region flexibility. However, L23 marks the beginning of the transition: MLP neurons contribute 1.76 total projection toward asparagine, and the representation starts shifting from 'what kind of position is this structurally' to 'what amino acid belongs here chemically.' Glycine remains the lens leader at 54% (L23), but the perception phase is ending.

The decisive push for asparagine occurs here. L28 shows 4.94 total delta (2.91 attention, 2.04 MLP), followed by L30 with 4.12 delta. MLP neurons deliver the critical votes: N29:1362 (1.256 proj), N30:2263 (0.783 proj), and N30:2733 (0.725 proj) all fire strongly for asparagine. Asparagine rises from 29% (L29) to 59% (L30), while glycine falls from 32% to 32%. This is where the model commits to the polar amide prediction.

The final lead change occurs at L32 when asparagine overtakes glycine (33.8% → 53.0%). Attention heads L31:17 (2.329 proj) and L31:19 (1.99 proj) provide refinement, while L32 MLP neurons make final adjustments. Despite L32 MLP showing -10.94 total projection (the model is suppressing alternatives), asparagine continues rising to 83% by L33 through attention-stream contributions.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L21
deep_dives.caption: L21:11 (2.001 projection) reads structural contacts with 98% attention to contact positions. With only 2 structural neighbors, this head provides limited constraint, allowing the representation to emphasize conformational flexibility over specific chemistry.

deep_dives.label: Turn-flexibility features L18
deep_dives.caption: L18 attention features encode turn-region character. F18:4071 (23.34 proj) and F18:9851 (21.68 proj) represent the structural flexibility that drives glycine's logit-lens dominance through mid-layers—this is perception of position type, not amino acid prediction.

deep_dives.label: Perception→Decision L23-24
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the transition: asparagine-specific prediction features appear (F24:3213 at 9.71 proj, F24:3435 at 8.79 proj) as the representation shifts from encoding structural context to predicting specific chemistry. Glycine's lens dominance begins collapsing here.

deep_dives.label: Decisive MLP votes L29-30
deep_dives.caption: The breakthrough for asparagine: N29:1362 delivers 1.256 projection (strongest single vote), followed by N30:2263 (0.783) and N30:2733 (0.725). These neurons vote specifically for asparagine, driving it from 29% to 59% and sealing the prediction.

deep_dives.label: Polar prediction channels L30
deep_dives.caption: L30 MLP features show strong polar prediction channels: F30:698 (26.37 proj), F30:7792 (24.96 proj), and F30:1691 (23.67 proj). These high-projection features encode the polar amide chemistry that distinguishes asparagine from the flexibility-driven glycine signal.

deep_dives.label: Final decision velocity L28-32
deep_dives.caption: Track the rapid probability shifts as asparagine overtakes glycine. L28 (4.94 delta), L30 (4.12 delta), and L31 (2.7 delta) show sustained positive velocity toward asparagine, while L32's lead change (G 33.8% → N 53.0%) marks the final commitment.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts asparagine by distinguishing between structural context (turn-region flexibility) and chemical requirements (polar amide). Through L1-23, the representation encodes conformational flexibility with minimal structural constraint (only 2 contacts), causing the logit lens to project toward glycine (87% at L22)—but this reflects position character, not prediction. The decision phase activates asparagine-specific channels at L24+, with MLP neurons at L29-30 delivering decisive votes (N29:1362 at 1.256 proj, N30:2263 at 0.783 proj). The strongest evidence is the late emergence of polar prediction features (F30:698, F30:7792) that override the structural flexibility signal and commit to the polar amide chemistry required at this position.
